Diagnosis. This species is easily distinguished by the metapostnotum with sparse hairs on most of its surface except a glabrous band close to the metanotum, the vertex of the head much elevated behind the ocelli, the yellowish, translucent tegula, through which the alary sclerites are easily seen, and the bilobed apex of the male T 7 . The male has a unique seventh sternum, with the apical lobes secondarily fused (
Fig. 20
).
